Package: truffle
Title: Create Teaching Datasets with Known Effects Hidden in Messy Data
Version: 0.1.6
Authors@R:
    person("Ian", "Hussey", email = "ian.hussey@unibe.ch",
           role = c("aut", "cre"),
           comment = c(ORCID = "0000-0001-8906-7559"))
Description: Generate datasets with known statistical effects (truffles) that
    students must rediscover, then bury them in realistic data-processing
    challenges (dirt) that must be cleaned first. Generated data contain
    demographics and item-level Likert responses, with known differences in
    sum-score means between conditions, known correlations between outcomes,
    and known 'Cronbach's' alpha per scale. Data can be made messy in many
    ways -- non-syntactic column names, duplicate rows, irregular missingness
    codes, mixed date formats, misspelled demographics, numbers with thousands
    separators and units, out-of-range values, disruptive header rows, and
    untidy columns holding more than one variable -- to create realistic
    wrangling exercises for teaching. The package is intentionally narrow: it
    currently generates a single study design (a between-groups experiment with
    equal group sizes) and relies on specific column-naming conventions.
